{"key":"post-12770951","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12770951</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;sk81681 said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;For best results do not layer,&amp;nbsp; Mix the substrate together with a layer of Verm on top.&lt;br /&gt;You absolutely want to case,&amp;nbsp; youll get bigger yields.&lt;br /&gt;PCing is preferred to pasterizing.&amp;nbsp; The only reason you would want to pasterize anything is if you have a large amount that would take days to cook otherwise.&lt;br /&gt;AS far as moisture loss, you can either spray very well for the first couple days after a flush or if the cake is small enough or you have something large enough to put it in, then definately dunk it completely submerged in water with .3% hydrogen peroxide (use 1 part HP for every 9 parts water).&amp;nbsp; Then re case. repeat.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It looks like you have reading to do my friend.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Casing is putting a non-nutritive layer over grains or a bulk substrate.&amp;nbsp; If you're going to case grains, you shake up the jar(s) of fully colonized grain spawn and pour them out into a tray.&amp;nbsp; Then, you cover with 1/2&quot; or so of your peat/verm casing mix.&amp;nbsp; You want to pasteurize casing layer mixes.&amp;nbsp; Sterilization leads to a high failure rate because all the beneficial microbes are killed off.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Never use peroxide for dunking, and it's awfully hard to dunk cased substrates anyway.&amp;nbsp; They can be flooded for a short time, and then the excess poured off, but one must be careful about breaking the substrate and casing layer if the tray flexes.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The original poster might find the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Casing-Layer-Preparation&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;casing layer prep video clip&lt;/a&gt; helpful.&amp;nbsp; It gives a demonstration of preparing the peat moss and vermiculite, and also a demonstration of a recommended pasteurization technique.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12771531</next>\n<prev>12770916</prev>\n<first>12770314</first>\n<last>12771531</last>\n<when>1277002910</when>\n<utime>06/20/10 06:01 AM</utime>\n</post>"}